## AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE

**Blog Gen instruction:** This section is your primary creative brief. Use this audience data to inform every paragraph, every sentence, every word choice. You are writing for this specific person with this specific intent. Satisfy them completely.

### Intent-Specific Audience Profile

**Who they are:** Women aged 17–25, high school and college graduates; mix of first-time salon visitors and regular nail clients; emotionally heightened — graduation day carries enormous significance for how they want to look and feel. Some are budget-conscious (uni students), some will splurge for the occasion. Active on TikTok and Pinterest for inspo.

**What they want from this post:** A curated edit that helps them feel confident in their nail choice before the big day. They want to see options that are genuinely gorgeous, feel current, and suit their personal aesthetic — not a wall of everything. They want the post to make the decision feel easier, not more overwhelming.

**What satisfies them:** Seeing designs that look realistic and achievable (not just celebrity/editorial); feeling like the writer actually understands that graduation day is about the whole look — outfit, photos, vibe — not just nails in isolation. Specific, opinionated guidance that says "this is why this works" not just "here are 50 ideas."

**What frustrates them:** Generic lists with no editorial curation; content that only shows long acrylics when they have short nails; school colour ideas that look tacky rather than personal; no guidance on how to book or prep; advice that feels recycled from last year.

### Top 5 Pain Points (Inspirational Intent Filter)

1. Feeling overwhelmed by too many options and not knowing what will actually suit them
2. Wanting to incorporate school colours without it looking like a costume or theme party accessory
3. Having short nails and feeling like all graduation nail inspo excludes them
4. Worrying their nails won't photograph well (diploma moment, cap-toss, group shots)
5. Not knowing whether to go trendy (vanilla chrome, bow nails) or timeless (French tip, nude) for an event they'll remember forever

### User Sentiment

Excited but anxious — graduation is a once-in-a-moment milestone and they desperately want their look to feel *right*, not just *nice*.

